To the upper end of the rod attach copper wire a foot long and as thick as a knitting needle, pointed like a needle. The rod can be attached to the wall of the house with twine (cord). On a tall house or barn, you can put two rods, one at each end, and connect them a wire stretched under the roof ridges. A house protected by such a device is not afraid of lightning, since the tip will attract it to itself and take it along a metal rod to the ground, and it will no longer harm anyone. In the same way, ships, on the top of the mast of which a point with a wire going down to the deck will be attached, and then along one of the shrouds and sheathing into the water, they will be protected from lightning "[7][6].